# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: epidemiological-modeling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] The definition assumes that no other individuals are infected or immunized (naturally or through vaccination).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Some definitions, such as that of the Australian Department of Health, add the absence of "any deliberate intervention in disease transmission".
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Thus values given in the literature only make sense in the given context and it is not recommended to compare values based on different models. $R_{0}$ does not by itself give an estimate of how fast an infection spreads in the population.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] The most important uses of $R_{0}$ are determining if an emerging infectious disease can spread in a population and determining what proportion of the population should be immunized through vaccination to eradicate a disease.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] In commonly used infection models, when $R_{0}>1$ the infection will be able to start spreading in a population, but not if $R_{0}<1$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Generally, the larger the value of $R_{0}$ , the harder it is to control the epidemic.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] For simple models, the proportion of the population that needs to be effectively immunized (meaning not susceptible to infection) to prevent sustained spread of the infection has to be larger than $1-1/R_{0}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] This is the so-called herd immunity threshold or herd immunity level.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Here, herd immunity means that the disease cannot spread in the population because each infected person, on average, can only transmit the infection to less than one other contact.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Conversely, the proportion of the population that remains susceptible to infection in the endemic equilibrium is $1/R_{0}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] However, this threshold is based on simple models that assume a fully mixed population with no structured relations between the individuals.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] For example, if there is some correlation between people's immunization (e.g., vaccination) status, then the formula $1-1/R_{0}$ may underestimate the herd immunity threshold.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] The basic reproduction number is affected by several factors, including the duration of infectivity of affected people, the contagiousness of the microorganism, and the number of susceptible people in the population that the infected people contact.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] The roots of the basic reproduction concept can be traced through the work of Ronald Ross, Alfred Lotka and others, but its first modern application in epidemiology was by George Macdonald in 1952, who constructed population models of the spread of malaria.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] In his work he called the quantity basic reproduction rate and denoted it by $Z_{0}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Compartmental models are a general modeling technique often applied to the mathematical modeling of infectious diseases.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] In these models, population members are assigned to 'compartments' with labels – for example, S, I, or R, (Susceptible, Infectious, or Recovered).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] These models can be used to estimate $R_{0}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Epidemics can be modeled as diseases spreading over networks of contact and disease transmission between people.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Nodes in these networks represent individuals and links (edges) between nodes represent the contact or disease transmission between them.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] where ${\beta }$ is the per-edge transmission rate, ${\gamma }$ is the recovery rate, ${\langle k\rangle }$ is the mean-degree (average degree) of the network and ${\langle k^{2}\rangle }$ is the second moment of the transmission network degree distribution.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] In populations that are not homogeneous, the definition of $R_{0}$ is more subtle.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] The definition must account for the fact that a typical infected individual may not be an average individual.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] As an extreme example, consider a population in which a small portion of the individuals mix fully with one another while the remaining individuals are all isolated.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] A disease may be able to spread in the fully mixed portion even though a randomly selected individual would lead to fewer than one secondary case.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] This is because the typical infected individual is in the fully mixed portion and thus is able to successfully cause infections.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] In general, if the individuals infected early in an epidemic are on average either more likely or less likely to transmit the infection than individuals infected late in the epidemic, then the computation of $R_{0}$ must account for this difference.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] An appropriate definition for $R_{0}$ in this case is "the expected number of secondary cases produced, in a completely susceptible population, produced by a typical infected individual".
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Some diseases have multiple possible latency periods, in which case the reproduction number for the disease overall is the sum of the reproduction number for each transition time into the disease.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] In reality, varying proportions of the population are immune to any given disease at any given time.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] To account for this, the **effective reproduction number** $R_{e}$ or R is used. $R_{t}$ is the average number of new infections caused by a single infected individual at time *t* in the partially susceptible population.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] It can be found by multiplying $R_{0}$ by the fraction *S* of the population that is susceptible.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] When the fraction of the population that is immune increases (i. e. the susceptible population *S* decreases) so much that $R_{e}$ drops below 1, herd immunity has been achieved and the number of cases occurring in the population will gradually decrease to zero.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Use of $R_{0}$ in the popular press has led to misunderstandings and distortions of its meaning. $R_{0}$ can be calculated from many different mathematical models and can be calculated from a single model multiple ways.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Each of these can give a different estimate of $R_{0}$ , which needs to be interpreted in the context of that model.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Therefore, the contagiousness of different infectious agents cannot be compared without recalculating $R_{0}$ with invariant assumptions. $R_{0}$ values for past outbreaks might not be valid for current outbreaks of the same disease.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Generally speaking, $R_{0}$ can be used as a threshold, even if calculated with different methods: if $R_{0}<1$ , the outbreak will die out, and if $R_{0}>1$ , the outbreak will expand.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] In some cases, for some models, values of $R_{0}<1$ can still lead to self-perpetuating outbreaks.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] This is particularly problematic if there are intermediate vectors between hosts (as is the case for zoonoses), such as malaria.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Therefore, comparisons between values from the "Values of $R_{0}$ of well-known contagious diseases" table should be conducted with caution.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Although $R_{0}$ cannot be modified through vaccination or other changes in population susceptibility, it can vary based on a number of biological, sociobehavioral, and environmental factors.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] It can also be modified by physical distancing and other public policy or social interventions, although some historical definitions exclude any deliberate intervention in reducing disease transmission, including nonpharmacological interventions.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] And indeed, whether nonpharmacological interventions are included in $R_{0}$ often depends on the paper, disease, and what if any intervention is being studied.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] This creates some confusion, because $R_{0}$ is not a constant; whereas most mathematical parameters with "nought" subscripts are constants.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] R depends on many factors, many of which need to be estimated.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Each of these factors adds to uncertainty in estimates of R .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Many of these factors are not important for informing public policy.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Therefore, public policy may be better served by metrics similar to R , but which are more straightforward to estimate, such as doubling time or half-life ( $t_{1/2}$ ).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Few of these methods agree with one another, even when starting with the same system of differential equations.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Even fewer actually calculate the average number of secondary infections.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Since $R_{0}$ is rarely observed in the field and is usually calculated via a mathematical model, this severely limits its usefulness.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Despite the difficulties in estimating $R_{0}$ mentioned in the previous section, estimates have been made for a number of genera, and are shown in this table.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Each genus may be composed of many species, strains, or variants.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] Estimations of $R_{0}$ for species, strains, and variants are typically less accurate than for genera, and so are provided in separate tables below for diseases of particular interest (influenza and COVID-19).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/basic-reproduction-number] In the 2011 film *Contagion*, a fictional medical disaster thriller, an epidemiologist explains the concept of $R_{0}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] These models originated in the early 20th century through pioneering epidemiological work by several mathematicians.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Key developments include Hamer's work in 1906, Ross's contributions in 1916, collaborative work by Ross and Hudson in 1917, the seminal Kermack and McKendrick model in 1927, and Kendall's work in 1956.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The historically significant Reed–Frost model, though often overlooked, also substantially influenced modern epidemiological modeling approaches.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Most implementations of compartmental models use ordinary differential equations (ODEs), providing deterministic results that are mathematically tractable.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] However, they can also be formulated within stochastic frameworks that incorporate randomness, offering more realistic representations of population dynamics at the cost of greater analytical complexity.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Beyond infectious disease modeling, the approach has been adapted for applications in population ecology, pharmacokinetics, chemical kinetics, and other fields requiring the study of transitions between defined states.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] For such investigations and to consult decision makers, often more complex models are used.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The **SIR model** is one of the simplest compartmental models, and many models are derivatives of this basic form.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] When a susceptible and an infectious individual come into "infectious contact", the susceptible individual contracts the disease and transitions to the infectious compartment.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] These are individuals who have been infected and are capable of infecting susceptible individuals.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] emoved (and immune) or deceased individuals.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] These are individuals who have been infected and have either recovered from the disease and entered the removed compartment, or died.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] It is assumed that the number of deaths is negligible with respect to the total population.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] This model is reasonably predictive for infectious diseases that are transmitted from human to human, and where recovery confers lasting resistance, such as measles, mumps, and rubella.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] These variables (**S**, **I**, and **R**) represent the number of people in each compartment at a particular time.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] To represent that the number of susceptible, infectious, and removed individuals may vary over time (even if the total population size remains constant), we make the precise numbers a function of *t* (time): **S**(*t*), **I**(*t*), and **R**(*t*).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] For a specific disease in a specific population, these functions may be worked out in order to predict possible outbreaks and bring them under control.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Note that in the SIR model, $R(0)$ and $R_{0}$ are different quantities – the former describes the number of recovered at *t* = 0 whereas the latter describes the ratio between the frequency of contacts to the frequency of recovery.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] As implied by the variable function of *t*, the model is dynamic in that the numbers in each compartment may fluctuate over time.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The importance of this dynamic aspect is most obvious in an endemic disease with a short infectious period, such as measles in the UK prior to the introduction of a vaccine in 1968.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Such diseases tend to occur in cycles of outbreaks due to the variation in number of susceptibles (S(*t*)) over time.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] During an epidemic, the number of susceptible individuals falls rapidly as more of them are infected and thus enter the infectious and removed compartments.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The disease cannot break out again until the number of susceptibles has built back up, e.g. as a result of offspring being born into the susceptible compartment.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Each member of the population typically progresses from susceptible to infectious to recovered.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] This can be shown as a flow diagram in which the boxes represent the different compartments and the arrows the transition between compartments (see diagram).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] For the full specification of the model, the arrows should be labeled with the transition rates between compartments.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Between *I* and *R*, the transition rate is assumed to be proportional to the number of infectious individuals which is $\gamma I$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] If an individual is infectious for an average time period D , then $\gamma =1/D$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] This is also equivalent to the assumption that the length of time spent by an individual in the infectious state is a random variable with an exponential distribution.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The "classical" SIR model may be modified by using more complex and realistic distributions for the I-R transition rate (e.g. the Erlang distribution).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] For the special case in which there is no removal from the infectious compartment ( $\gamma =0$ ), the SIR model reduces to a very simple SI model, which has a logistic solution, in which every individual eventually becomes infected.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The dynamics of an epidemic, for example, the flu, are often much faster than the dynamics of birth and death, therefore, birth and death are often omitted in simple compartmental models.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] This model was for the first time proposed by William Ogilvy Kermack and Anderson Gray McKendrick as a special case of what we now call Kermack–McKendrick theory, and followed work McKendrick had done with Ronald Ross.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] This system is non-linear, however it is possible to derive its analytic solution in implicit form.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] expressing in mathematical terms the constancy of population N .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Note that the above relationship implies that one need only study the equation for two of the three variables.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] the so-called basic reproduction number (also called basic reproduction ratio).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] This ratio is derived as the expected number of new infections (these new infections are sometimes called secondary infections) from a single infection in a population where all subjects are susceptible.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] This idea can probably be more readily seen if we say that the typical time between contacts is $T_{c}=\beta ^{-1}$ , and the typical time until removal is $T_{r}=\gamma ^{-1}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] where $S(0)$ and $R(0)$ are the initial numbers of, respectively, susceptible and removed subjects.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] (note that the infectious compartment empties in this limit).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] This shows that at the end of an epidemic that conforms to the simple assumptions of the SIR model, unless $s_{0}=0$ , not all individuals of the population have been removed, so some must remain susceptible.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] A driving force leading to the end of an epidemic is a decline in the number of infectious individuals.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The epidemic does not typically end because of a complete lack of susceptible individuals.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The role of both the basic reproduction number and the initial susceptibility are extremely important.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] i.e., there will be a proper epidemic outbreak with an increase of the number of the infectious (which can reach a considerable fraction of the population).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] i.e., independently from the initial size of the susceptible population the disease can never cause a proper epidemic outbreak.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] As a consequence, it is clear that both the basic reproduction number and the initial susceptibility are extremely important.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] models the transition rate from the compartment of susceptible individuals to the compartment of infectious individuals, so that it is called the force of infection.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Capasso and, afterwards, other authors have proposed nonlinear forces of infection to model more realistically the contagion process.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] In 2014, Harko and coauthors derived an exact so-called analytical solution (involving an integral that can only be calculated numerically) to the SIR model.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Here $\xi (t)$ can be interpreted as the expected number of transmissions an individual has received by time t .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The two solutions are related by $e^{-\xi (t)}=u$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Effectively the same result can be found in the original work by Kermack and McKendrick.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] These solutions may be easily understood by noting that all of the terms on the right-hand sides of the original differential equations are proportional to I .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The equations may thus be divided through by I , and the time rescaled so that the differential operator on the left-hand side becomes simply $d/d\tau$ , where $d\tau =Idt$ , i.e. $\tau =\int Idt$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The differential equations are now all linear, and the third equation, of the form $dR/d\tau =$ const., shows that $\tau$ and R (and $\xi$ above) are simply linearly related.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The approximant involves the Lambert W function which is part of all basic data visualization software such as Microsoft Excel, MATLAB, and Mathematica.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] While Kendall considered the so-called all-time SIR model where the initial conditions $S(0)$ , $I(0)$ , and $R(0)$ are coupled through the above relations, Kermack and McKendrick proposed to study the more general semi-time case, for which $S(0)$ and $I(0)$ are both arbitrary.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] This latter version, denoted as semi-time SIR model, makes predictions only for future times $t>0$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] An analytic approximant and exact expressions for the final values are available for the semi-time SIR model as well.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Numerical solutions to the SIR model can be found in the literature.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] An example is using the model to analyze COVID-19 spreading data.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Thus when this person recovered, there are two people still infectious directly got from this person and $R_{0}=2$ , i.e. the number of infectious people doubled in one cycle of 5 days.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The data simulated by the model with $R_{0}=2$ or real data fitted will yield a doubling of the number of infectious people faster than 5 days because the two infected people are infecting people.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The model use $SI$ to represent these factors but it indeed is referenced to the initial stage when no action is taken to prevent the spread and all population is susceptible, thus all changes are absorbed by the change of $\beta$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] $\gamma$ is usually more stable over time assuming when the infectious person shows symptoms, she/he will seek medical attention or be self-isolated.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] So if we find $R_{t}$ changes, most probably the behaviors of people in the community have changed from their normal patterns before the outbreak, or the disease has mutated to a new form.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Costive massive detection and isolation of susceptible close contacts have effects on reducing $1/\gamma$ but whose efficiencies are under debate.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] This debate is largely on the uncertainty of the number of days reduced from after infectious or detectable whichever comes first to before a symptom shows up for an infected susceptible person.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] If the person is infectious after symptoms show up, or detection only works for a person with symptoms, then these prevention methods are not necessary, and self-isolation and/or medical attention is the best way to cut the $1/\gamma$ values.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The typical onset of the COVID-19 infectious period is in the order of one day from the symptoms showing up, making massive detection with typical frequency in a few days useless.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] It corrects the effective/transmissible interaction between an infectious person and the rest of the community when many of the interaction is immune in the middle to late stages of the disease spreading.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Thus, when $R_{e}>1$ , we will see an exponential-like outbreak; when $R_{e}=1$ , a steady state reached and no number of infectious people changes over time; and when $R_{e}<1$ , the disease decays and fades away over time.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Using the differential equations of the SIR model and converting them to numerical discrete forms, one can set up the recursive equations and calculate the S, I, and R populations with any given initial conditions but accumulate errors over a long calculation time from the reference point.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Sometimes a convergence test is needed to estimate the errors.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Given a set of initial conditions and the disease-spreading data, one can also fit the data with the SIR model and pull out the three reproduction numbers when the errors are usually negligible due to the short time step from the reference point.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Any point of the time can be used as the initial condition to predict the future after it using this numerical model with assumption of time-evolved parameters such as population, $R_{t}$ , and $\gamma$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] However, away from this reference point, errors will accumulate over time thus convergence test is needed to find an optimal time step for more accurate results.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Also, it can be used to directly calculate the threshold population of vaccination/immunization for the herd immunity stage by setting $R_{t}=R_{0}$ , and $R_{E}=1$ , i.e. $S=N/R_{0}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Consider a population characterized by a death rate $\mu$ and birth rate $\Lambda$ , and where a communicable disease is spreading.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The point EE is called the Endemic Equilibrium (the disease is not totally eradicated and remains in the population).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] McKendrick created a model in which they considered a fixed population with only three compartments: susceptible, $S(t)$ ; infected, $I(t)$ ; and recovered, $R(t)$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Using a fixed population, $N=S(t)+I(t)+R(t)$ in the three functions resolves that the value N should remain constant within the simulation, if a simulation is used to solve the SIR model.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Alternatively, the analytic approximant can be used without performing a simulation.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] These are the number of people in the susceptible, infected and removed categories at time equals zero.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] If the SIR model is assumed to hold at all times, these initial conditions are not independent.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Subsequently, the flow model updates the three variables for every time point with set values for $\beta$ and $\gamma$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The simulation first updates the infected from the susceptible and then the removed category is updated from the infected category for the next time point (t=1).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] This describes the flow persons between the three categories.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] During an epidemic the susceptible category is not shifted with this model, $\beta$ changes over the course of the epidemic and so does $\gamma$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] These variables determine the length of the epidemic and would have to be updated with each cycle.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Then, let $\beta$ be the multiplication of a and b .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] This is the transmission probability times the contact rate.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Besides, an infected individual makes contact with b persons per unit time whereas only a fraction, $S/N$ of them are susceptible.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Thus, we have every infective can infect $abS=\beta S$ susceptible persons, and therefore, the whole number of susceptibles infected by infectives per unit time is $\beta SI$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] For the second and third equations, consider the population leaving the susceptible class as equal to the number entering the infected class.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] However, a number equal to the fraction $\gamma$ (which represents the mean recovery/death rate, or $1/\gamma$ the mean infective period) of infectives are leaving this class per unit time to enter the removed class.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] These processes which occur simultaneously are referred to as the Law of Mass Action, a widely accepted idea that the rate of contact between two groups in a population is proportional to the size of each of the groups concerned.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Finally, it is assumed that the rate of infection and recovery is much faster than the time scale of births and deaths and therefore, these factors are ignored in this model.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The only steady state solution to the classic SIR model as defined by the differential equations above is I=0, S and R can then take any values.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] The model can be changed while retaining three compartments to give a steady-state endemic solution by adding some input to the S compartment.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Also, compartments for vaccination, detection, or infected vectors like fleas, ticks, or mosquitoes can be added.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p01] Compartmental models can also be used to model multiple risk groups, and even the interaction of multiple pathogens.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Some infections, for example, those from the common cold and influenza, do not confer any long-lasting immunity.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Such infections may give temporary resistance but do not give long-term immunity upon recovery from infection, and individuals become susceptible again.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] It is possible to find an analytical solution to this model (by making a transformation of variables: $I=y^{-1}$ and substituting this into the mean-field equations), such that the basic reproduction rate is greater than unity.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] As the system is assumed to be closed, the susceptible population is then $S(t)=N-I(t)$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Whenever the integer nature of the number of agents is evident (populations with fewer than tens of thousands of individuals), inherent fluctuations in the disease spreading process caused by discrete agents result in uncertainties.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In this scenario, the evolution of the disease predicted by compartmental equations deviates significantly from the observed results.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] These uncertainties may even cause the epidemic to end earlier than predicted by the compartmental equations.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] As a special case, one obtains the usual logistic function by assuming $\gamma =0$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] This can be also considered in the SIR model with $R=0$ , i.e. no removal will take place.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In the long run, in the SI model, all individuals will become infected.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The *Susceptible-Infectious-Recovered-Deceased model* differentiates between *Recovered* (meaning specifically individuals having survived the disease and now immune) and *Deceased*.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The SIRD model has semi analytical solutions based on the four parts method.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] where $\beta ,\gamma ,\mu$ are the rates of infection, recovery, and mortality, respectively.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The *Susceptible-Infectious-Recovered-Vaccinated model* is an extended SIR model that accounts for vaccination of the susceptible population.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] where $\beta ,\gamma ,v$ are the rates of infection, recovery, and vaccination, respectively.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] For the semi-time initial conditions $S(0)=(1-\eta )N$ , $I(0)=\eta N$ , $R(0)=V(0)=0$ and constant ratios $k=\gamma (t)/\beta (t)$ and $b=v(t)/\beta (t)$ the model had been solved approximately.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The occurrence of a pandemic outburst requires $k+b<1-2\eta$ and there is a critical reduced vaccination rate $b_{c}$ beyond which the steady-state size $S_{\infty }$ of the susceptible compartment remains relatively close to $S(0)$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Arbitrary initial conditions satisfying $S(0)+I(0)+R(0)+V(0)=N$ can be mapped to the solved special case with $R(0)=V(0)=0$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The numerical solution of this model to calculate the real-time reproduction number $R_{t}$ of COVID-19 can be practiced based on information from the different populations in a community.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Numerical solution is a commonly used method to analyze complicated kinetic networks when the analytical solution is difficult to obtain or limited by requirements such as boundary conditions or special parameters.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] It uses recursive equations to calculate the next step by converting the numerical integration into Riemann sum of discrete time steps e.g., use yesterday's principal and interest rate to calculate today's interest which assumes the interest rate is fixed during the day.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The calculation contains projected errors if the analytical corrections on the numerical step size are not included, e.g. when the interest rate of annual collection is simplified to 12 times the monthly rate, a projected error is introduced.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Thus the calculated results will carry accumulative errors when the time step is far away from the reference point and a convergence test is needed to estimate the error.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] However, this error is usually acceptable for data fitting.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] When fitting a set of data with a close time step, the error is relatively small because the reference point is nearby compared to when predicting a long period of time after a reference point.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Once the real-time $R_{t}$ is pulled out, one can compare it to the basic reproduction number $R_{0}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Before the vaccination, $R_{t}$ gives the policy maker and general public a measure of the efficiency of social mitigation activities such as social distancing and face masking simply by dividing ${\frac {R_{t}}{R_{0}}}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Under massive vaccination, the goal of disease control is to reduce the effective reproduction number $R_{e}={\frac {R_{t}S}{N}}<1$ , where S is the number of susceptible population at the time and N is the total population.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] When $R_{e}<1$ , the spreading decays and daily infected cases go down.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The *susceptible-infected-recovered-vaccinated-deceased* (SIRVD) epidemic compartment model extends the SIR model to include the effects of vaccination campaigns and time-dependent fatality rates on epidemic outbreaks.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] It encompasses the SIR, SIRV, SIRD, and SI models as special cases, with individual time-dependent rates governing transitions between different fractions.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] where $a(t),v(t),\mu (t),\psi (t)$ are the infection, vaccination, recovery, and fatality rates, respectively.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] For the semi-time initial conditions $S(0)=1-\eta$ , $I(0)=\eta$ , $R(0)=V(0)=D(0)=0$ and constant ratios $k=\mu (t)/a(t)$ , $b=v(t)/a(t)$ , and $q=\psi (t)/a(t)$ the model had been solved approximately, and exactly for some special cases, irrespective of the functional form of $a(t)$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The temporal dependence of the infected fraction $I(\tau )$ and the rate of new infections $j(\tau )=S(\tau )I(\tau )$ differs when considering the effects of vaccinations and when the real-time dependence of fatality and recovery rates diverge.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] These differences have been highlighted for stationary ratios and gradually decreasing fatality rates.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The case of stationary ratios allows one to construct a diagnostics method to extract analytically all SIRVD model parameters from measured COVID-19 data of a completed pandemic wave.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The SIRVB model adds a breakthrough pathway in the SIRV model.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] where infection rate $a(t)$ can be write as $\beta (t)/N$ , recovery rate $\mu (t)$ can be simplified to a constant $\gamma$ , $v(t)$ is the vaccination rate, $b(t)$ is the break through ratio or fraction of immuned people susceptible to reinfection (<1).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] For many infections, including measles, babies are not born into the susceptible compartment but are immune to the disease for the first few months of life due to protection from maternal antibodies (passed across the placenta and additionally through colostrum).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] This added detail can be shown by including an M class (for maternally derived immunity) at the beginning of the model.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Some people who have had an infectious disease such as tuberculosis never completely recover and continue to carry the infection, whilst not suffering the disease themselves.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] They may then move back into the infectious compartment and suffer symptoms (as in tuberculosis) or they may continue to infect others in their carrier state, while not suffering symptoms.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The most famous example of this is probably Mary Mallon, who infected 22 people with typhoid fever.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] For many important infections, there is a significant latency period during which individuals have been infected but are not yet infectious themselves.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] During this period the individual is in compartment *E* (for exposed).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] We have $S+E+I+R=N,$ but this is only constant because of the simplifying assumption that birth and death rates are equal; in general N is a variable.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] is stable (i.e. it has its Floquet's eigenvalues inside the unit circle in the complex plane).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The SEIS model is like the SEIR model (above) except that no immunity is acquired at the end.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In this model an infection does not leave any immunity thus individuals that have recovered return to being susceptible, moving back into the *S*(*t*) compartment.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] For the case of a disease, with the factors of passive immunity, and a latency period there is the MSEIR model.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] An MSEIRS model is similar to the MSEIR, but the immunity in the R class would be temporary, so that individuals would regain their susceptibility when the temporary immunity ended.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] When developing more detailed models for in-depth analysis, models are mostly generated for specific outbreak scenarios of specific diseases, including compartments for targeted research questions like hospitalization compartments or detection dynamics.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Even though those models are often tailored for specific situations, there are complex models, still usable for a broad variety of different diseases.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] One of those attempts to create a general model includes twelve compartments, extending the well-known SEIR model by a second stage of infection, detection compartments, and two doses of vaccination.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Additionally smear infections are incorporated via an external Pathogen P and a simplistic vector population is included by $S_{V}$ and $I_{V}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Moreover population dynamics like birth and death processes can be included.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Such complex models enable a deeper understanding of infection dynamics and the introduction of different pharmaceutical and non-pharmaceutical interventions.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] It is well known that the probability of getting a disease is not constant in time.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] As a pandemic progresses, reactions to the pandemic may change the contact rates which are assumed constant in the simpler models.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Counter-measures such as masks, social distancing, and lockdown will alter the contact rate in a way to reduce the speed of the pandemic.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In addition, Some diseases are seasonal, such as the common cold viruses, which are more prevalent during winter.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] With childhood diseases, such as measles, mumps, and rubella, there is a strong correlation with the school calendar, so that during the school holidays the probability of getting such a disease dramatically decreases.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] (the dynamics of recovered easily follows from $R=N-S-I$ ), i.e. a nonlinear set of differential equations with periodically varying parameters.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] It is well known that this class of dynamical systems may undergo very interesting and complex phenomena of nonlinear parametric resonance.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] whereas if the integral is greater than one the disease will not die out and there may be such resonances.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] For example, considering the periodically varying contact rate as the 'input' of the system one has that the output is a periodic function whose period is a multiple of the period of the input.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] This allowed to give a contribution to explain the poly-annual (typically biennial) epidemic outbreaks of some infectious diseases as interplay between the period of the contact rate oscillations and the pseudo-period of the damped oscillations near the endemic equilibrium.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Remarkably, in some cases, the behavior may also be quasi-periodic or even chaotic.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Spatiotemporal compartmental models describe not the total number, but the density of susceptible/infective/recovered persons.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Consequently, they also allow to model the distribution of infected persons in space.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Thereby, one obtains a reaction-diffusion equation.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] (Note that, for dimensional reasons, the parameter $\beta$ has to be changed compared to the simple SIR model.) Early models of this type have been used to model the spread of the black death in Europe.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Extensions of this model have been used to incorporate, e.g., effects of nonpharmaceutical interventions such as social distancing.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The SIR model has been studied on networks of various kinds in order to model a more realistic form of connection than the homogeneous mixing condition which is usually required.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] A simple model for epidemics on networks in which an individual has a probability p of being infected by each of his infected neighbors in a given time step leads to results similar to giant component formation on Erdos Renyi random graphs.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] This model captures the class of vector transmitted infectious diseases such as Dengue, Malaria (transmission by mosquitoes), pestilence (transmission by fleas), and others.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Dynamics of epidemics depend on how people's behavior changes in time.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] For example, at the beginning of the epidemic, people are ignorant and careless, then, after the outbreak of epidemics and alarm, they begin to comply with the various restrictions and the spreading of epidemics may decline.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Over time, some people get tired/frustrated by the restrictions and stop following them (exhaustion), especially if the number of new cases drops down.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] After resting for some time, they can follow the restrictions again.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] But during this pause the second wave can come and become even stronger than the first one.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The social physics models of social stress complement the classical epidemics models.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The simplest SIR-social stress (SIRSS) model is organised as follows.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The susceptible individuals (S) can be split in three subgroups by the types of behavior: ignorant or unaware of the epidemic (Sign), rationally resistant (Sres), and exhausted (Sexh) that do not react on the external stimuli (this is a sort of refractory period).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In other words: S(t) = Sign(t) + Sres(t) + Sexh(t).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] has different reaction rate constants $\beta$ for Sign, Sres, and Sexh.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Presumably, for Sres, $\beta$ is lower than for Sign and Sign.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The differences between countries are concentrated in two kinetic constants: the rate of mobilization and the rate of exhaustion calculated for COVID-19 epidemic in 13 countries.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Based on the classical SIR model, a Korteweg-de Vries (KdV)–SIR equation and its analytical solution have been proposed to illustrate the fundamental dynamics of an epidemic wave, the dependence of solutions on parameters, and the dependence of predictability horizons on various types of solutions.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] $S_{o}$ indicates the initial value of the state variable S .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Parameters $\sigma _{o}$ (σ-naught) and $R_{o}$ (R-naught) are the time-independent relative growth rate and basic reproduction number, respectively. $I_{max}$ presents the maximum of the state variables I (for the number of infected persons).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The KdV-SIR equation shares the same form as the Korteweg–De Vries equation in the traveling wave coordinate.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] which represents a solitary wave solution.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Modeling a full population of possibly millions people using two constants $\beta$ and $\gamma$ seem far fetched; each individual has personal characteristics that influence the propagation : immunity status, contact habits and so on.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] So it is interesting to know what happens if, for instance, $\beta$ and $\gamma$ are not two constants but some random variables (a pair for each individual).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] This procedure has several names : "heterogeneous model", "structuration" (see also below for age structured models) or "Bayesian" view.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Surprising results emerge, for instance it was proved in that the number of infected at the peak of a heterogeneous epidemic is smaller than the deterministic epidemic having same average $\beta$ ; the same holds true for the total epidemic size $S(0)-S(\infty )$ and other models, e.g.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The SIR model can be modified to model vaccination.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Typically these introduce an additional compartment to the SIR model, V , for vaccinated individuals.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In presence of a communicable diseases, one of the main tasks is that of eradicating it via prevention measures and, if possible, via the establishment of a mass vaccination program.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] where V is the class of vaccinated subjects.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] the vaccination program is not successful in eradicating the disease, on the contrary, it will remain endemic, although at lower levels than the case of absence of vaccinations.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] This means that the mathematical model suggests that for a disease whose basic reproduction number may be as high as 18 one should vaccinate at least 94.4% of newborns in order to eradicate the disease.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Modern societies are facing the challenge of "rational" exemption, i.e. the family's decision to not vaccinate children as a consequence of a "rational" comparison between the perceived risk from infection and that from getting damages from the vaccine.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] i.e. the baseline vaccination rate should be greater than the "mandatory vaccination" threshold, which, in case of exemption, cannot hold.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Thus, "rational" exemption might be myopic since it is based only on the current low incidence due to high vaccine coverage, instead taking into account future resurgence of infection due to coverage decline.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] This strategy repeatedly vaccinates a defined age-cohort (such as young children or the elderly) in a susceptible population over time.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Using this strategy, the block of susceptible individuals is then immediately removed, making it possible to eliminate an infectious disease, (such as measles), from the entire population.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Every T time units a constant fraction p of susceptible subjects is vaccinated in a relatively short (with respect to the dynamics of the disease) time.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] A huge literature recognizes that the vaccination can be seen as a game: in a population where everybody is vaccinated any epidemic will die off immediately so an additional person will have no interest to vaccinate at all.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] On the contrary, a person arriving in a population where nobody is vaccinated will have all incentives to vaccinate (the epidemic will break loose in such a population).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] So, it seems that the individual has interest to do the opposite of the population as a whole.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] But the population is the sum of all individuals, and the previous affirmation should be false.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] So, in fact, a Nash equilibrium is reached.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Technical tools to treat such situations involve game theory or modern tools such as Mean-field game theory.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Age has a deep influence on the disease spread rate in a population, especially the contact rate.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] This rate summarizes the effectiveness of contacts between susceptible and infectious subjects.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] is the force of infection, which, of course, will depend, though the contact kernel $k(a,a_{1};t)$ on the interactions between the ages.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] where $\varphi _{j}(a),j=s,i,r$ are the fertilities of the adults.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] A basic reproduction number can be calculated as the spectral radius of an appropriate functional operator.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] One way to calculate $R_{0}$ is to average the expected number of new infections over all possible infected types.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The next-generation method is a general method of deriving $R_{0}$ when more than one class of infectives is involved.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] This method, originally introduced by Diekmann *et al*.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] (1990), can be used for models with underlying age structure or spatial structure, among other possibilities.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Consider a sexually transmitted disease.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In a naive population where almost everyone is susceptible, but the infection seed, if the expected number of gender 1 is f and the expected number of infected gender 2 is m , we can know how many would be infected in the next-generation.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Diagonal elements are zero because people of the same gender cannot transmit the disease to each other but, for example, each f can transmit the disease to m , on average.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Meaning that each element $g_{ij}$ is a reproduction number, but one where who infects whom is accounted for.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] If generation a is represented with $\phi _{a}$ then the next generation $\phi _{a+1}$ would be $G\phi _{a}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The spectral radius of the next-generation matrix is the basic reproduction number, $R_{0}=\rho (G)={\sqrt {mf}}$ , that is here, the geometric mean of the expected number of each gender in the next-generation.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Note that multiplication factors f and m alternate because, the infectious person has to 'pass through' a second gender before it can enter a new host of the first gender.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In other words, it takes two generations to get back to the same type, and every two generations numbers are multiplied by m × f .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The average per generation multiplication factor is therefore ${\sqrt {mf}}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Note that G is a non-negative matrix so it has single, unique, positive, real eigenvalue which is strictly greater than all the others.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In mathematical modelling of infectious disease, the dynamics of spreading is usually described through a set of non-linear ordinary differential equations (ODE).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] So there is always n coupled equations of form ${\dot {C_{i}}}={\operatorname {d} \!C_{i} \over \operatorname {d} \!t}=f(C_{1},C_{2},...,C_{n})$ which shows how the number of people in compartment $C_{i}$ changes over time.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Compartmental models have a disease-free equilibrium (DFE) meaning that it is possible to find an equilibrium while setting the number of infected people to zero, $I=0$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In other words, as a rule, there is an infection-free steady state.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] This solution, also usually ensures that the disease-free equilibrium is also an equilibrium of the system.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] There is another fixed point known as an Endemic Equilibrium (EE) where the disease is not totally eradicated and remains in the population.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] To calculate $R_{0}$ , the first step is to linearise around the disease-free equilibrium (DFE), but for the infected subsystem of non-linear ODEs which describe the production of new infections and changes in state among infected individuals.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Epidemiologically, the linearisation reflects that $R_{0}$ characterizes the potential for initial spread of an infectious person in a naive population, assuming the change in the susceptible population is negligible during the initial spread.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] A linear system of ODEs can always be described by a matrix.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] So, the next step is to construct a linear positive operator that provides the next generation of infected people when applied to the present generation.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Note that this operator (matrix) is responsible for the number of infected people, not all the compartments.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Iteration of this operator describes the initial progression of infection within the heterogeneous population.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] So comparing the spectral radius of this operator to unity determines whether the generations of infected people grow or not. $R_{0}$ can be written as a product of the infection rate near the disease-free equilibrium and average duration of infectiousness.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] It is used to find the peak and final size of an epidemic.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] As described in the example above, so many epidemic processes can be described with a SIR‌ model.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] However, for many important infections, such as COVID-19, there is a significant latency period during which individuals have been infected but are not yet infectious themselves.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Here, the formation of the next-generation matrix from the SEIR‌ model involves determining two compartments, infected and non-infected, since they are the populations that spread the infection.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] So we only need to model the exposed, ***E***, and infected, ***I***, compartments.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Consider a population characterized by a death rate $\mu$ and birth rate $\lambda$ where a communicable disease is spreading.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] As in the previous example, we can use the transition rates between the compartments per capita such that $\beta$ be the infection rate, $\gamma$ be the recovery rate, and $\kappa$ be the rate at which a latent individual becomes infectious.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Let $F_{i}(\mathrm {x} )$ be the rate of appearance of new infections in compartment *i* such that it includes only infections that are newly arising, but does not include terms which describe the transfer of infectious individuals from one infected compartment to another.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] We now can form the next-generation matrix (operator) $G=FV^{-1}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Basically, F is a non-negative matrix which represents the infection rates near the equilibrium, and V is an M-matrix for linear transition terms making $V^{-1}$ a matrix which represents the average duration of infectiousness.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The basic reproduction number can be estimated through examining detailed transmission chains or through genomic sequencing.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] However, it is most frequently calculated using epidemiological models.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] During an epidemic, typically the number of diagnosed infections $N(t)$ over time t is known.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In order to estimate $R_{0}$ , assumptions are necessary about the time delay between infection and diagnosis and the time between infection and starting to be infectious.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Latent infectious: an individual is infected, has no symptoms, but does infect others.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The average duration of the latent infectious state is $\tau _{I}$ .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The individual infects $R_{0}$ other individuals during this period.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Isolation after diagnosis: measures are taken to prevent further infections, for example by isolating the infected person.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] This is a SEIR model and $R_{0}$ may be written in the following form $R_{0}=1+K(\tau _{E}+\tau _{I})+K^{2}\tau _{E}\tau _{I}.$ This estimation method has been applied to COVID-19 and SARS.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In the special case $\tau _{I}=0$ , this model results in $R_{0}=1+K\tau _{E}$ , which is different from the simple model above ( $R_{0}=\exp(K\tau _{E})$ ).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The difference is due to a subtle difference in the underlying growth model; the matrix equation above assumes that newly infected patients are currently already contributing to infections, while in fact infections only occur due to the number infected at $\tau _{E}$ ago.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] A more correct treatment would require the use of delay differential equations.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Latent period is the transition time between contagion event and disease manifestation.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In cases of diseases with varying latent periods, the basic reproduction number can be calculated as the sum of the reproduction numbers for each transition time into the disease.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] An example of this is tuberculosis (TB).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In the case of some diseases such as AIDS and hepatitis B, it is possible for the offspring of infected parents to be born infected.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] This transmission of the disease down from the mother is referred to as vertical transmission.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The influx of additional members into the infected category can be considered within the model by including a fraction of the newborn members in the infected compartment.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Diseases transmitted from human to human indirectly, i.e. malaria spread by way of mosquitoes, are transmitted through a vector.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In these cases, the infection transfers from human to insect and an epidemic model must include both species, generally requiring many more compartments than a model for direct transmission.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The deterministic models presented here are valid only in case of sufficiently large populations, and as such should be used cautiously.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] These models are only valid in the thermodynamic limit, where the population is effectively infinite.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In stochastic models, the long-time endemic equilibrium derived above, does not hold, as there is a finite probability that the number of infected individuals drops below one in a system.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] In a true system then, the pathogen may not propagate, as no host will be infected.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] But, in deterministic mean-field models, the number of infected can take on real, namely, non-integer values of infected hosts, and the number of hosts in the model can be less than one, but more than zero, thereby allowing the pathogen in the model to propagate.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] The reliability of compartmental models is limited to compartmental applications.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] One of the possible extensions of mean-field models considers the spreading of epidemics on a network based on percolation theory concepts.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/compartmental-models-in-epidemiology-p02] Stochastic epidemic models have been studied on different networks and more recently applied to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/force-of-infection] In epidemiology, **force of infection** (denoted $\lambda$ ) is the rate at which susceptible individuals acquire an infectious disease.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/force-of-infection] Because it takes account of susceptibility it can be used to compare the rate of transmission between different groups of the population for the same infectious disease, or even between different infectious diseases.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/force-of-infection] That is to say, $\lambda$ is directly proportional to $\beta$ ; the effective transmission rate.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/force-of-infection] Such a calculation is difficult because not all new infections are reported, and it is often difficult to know how many susceptibles were exposed.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/force-of-infection] However, $\lambda$ can be calculated for an infectious disease in an endemic state if homogeneous mixing of the population and a rectangular population distribution (such as that generally found in developed countries), rather than a pyramid, is assumed.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/force-of-infection] where A is the average age of infection.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/force-of-infection] In other words, A is the average time spent in the susceptible group before becoming infected.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/force-of-infection] The rate of becoming infected ( $\lambda$ ) is therefore $1/A$ (since rate is 1/time).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/force-of-infection] The advantage of this method of calculating $\lambda$ is that data on the average age of infection is very easily obtainable, even if not all cases of the disease are reported.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Mathematical models can project how infectious diseases progress to show the likely outcome of an epidemic (including in plants) and help inform public health and plant health interventions.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Models use basic assumptions or collected statistics along with mathematics to find parameters for various infectious diseases and use those parameters to calculate the effects of different interventions, like mass vaccination programs.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The modelling can help decide which intervention(s) to avoid and which to trial, or can predict future growth patterns, etc.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The modelling of infectious diseases is a tool that has been used to study the mechanisms by which diseases spread, to predict the future course of an outbreak and to evaluate strategies to control an epidemic.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The first scientist who systematically tried to quantify causes of death was John Graunt in his book *Natural and Political Observations made upon the Bills of Mortality*, in 1662.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The bills he studied were listings of numbers and causes of deaths published weekly.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Graunt's analysis of causes of death is considered the beginning of the "theory of competing risks" which according to Daley and Gani is "a theory that is now well established among modern epidemiologists".
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The earliest account of mathematical modelling of spread of disease was carried out in 1760 by Daniel Bernoulli.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Trained as a physician, Bernoulli created a mathematical model to defend the practice of inoculating against smallpox.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The calculations from this model showed that universal inoculation against smallpox would increase the life expectancy from 26 years 7 months to 29 years 9 months.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Daniel Bernoulli's work preceded the modern understanding of germ theory.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] In the early 20th century, William Hamer and Ronald Ross applied the law of mass action to explain epidemic behaviour.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The 1920s saw the emergence of compartmental models.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The Kermack–McKendrick epidemic model (1927) and the Reed–Frost epidemic model (1928) both describe the relationship between susceptible, infected and immune individuals in a population.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The Kermack–McKendrick epidemic model was successful in predicting the behavior of outbreaks very similar to that observed in many recorded epidemics.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Recently, agent-based models (ABMs) have been used in exchange for simpler compartmental models.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] For example, epidemiological ABMs have been used to inform public health (nonpharmaceutical) interventions against the spread of SARS-CoV-2.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Epidemiological ABMs, in spite of their complexity and requiring high computational power, have been criticized for simplifying and unrealistic assumptions.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Still, they can be useful in informing decisions regarding mitigation and suppression measures in cases when ABMs are accurately calibrated.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Models are only as good as the assumptions on which they are based.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] If a model makes predictions that are out of line with observed results and the mathematics is correct, the initial assumptions must change to make the model useful.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] "Stochastic" means being or having a random variable.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] A stochastic model is a tool for estimating probability distributions of potential outcomes by allowing for random variation in one or more inputs over time.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Stochastic models depend on the chance variations in risk of exposure, disease and other illness dynamics.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Statistical agent-level disease dissemination in small or large populations can be determined by stochastic methods.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] When dealing with large populations, as in the case of tuberculosis, deterministic or compartmental mathematical models are often used.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] In a deterministic model, individuals in the population are assigned to different subgroups or compartments, each representing a specific stage of the epidemic.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The transition rates from one class to another are mathematically expressed as derivatives, hence the model is formulated using differential equations.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] While building such models, it must be assumed that the population size in a compartment is differentiable with respect to time and that the epidemic process is deterministic.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] In other words, the changes in population of a compartment can be calculated using only the history that was used to develop the model.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Formally, these models belong to the class of deterministic models; however, they incorporate heterogeneous social features into the dynamics, such as individuals' levels of sociality, opinion, wealth, geographic location, which profoundly influence disease propagation.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] These models are typically represented by partial differential equations, in contrast to classical models described as systems of ordinary differential equations.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Following the derivation principles of kinetic theory, they provide a more rigorous description of epidemic dynamics by starting from agent-based interactions.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] A common explanation for the growth of epidemics holds that 1 person infects 2, those 2 infect 4 and so on and so on with the number of infected doubling every generation.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] It is analogous to a game of tag where 1 person tags 2, those 2 tag 4 others who've never been tagged and so on.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] As this game progresses it becomes increasing frenetic as the tagged run past the previously tagged to hunt down those who have never been tagged.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Thus this model of an epidemic leads to a curve that grows exponentially until it crashes to zero as all the population have been infected. i.e. no herd immunity and no peak and gradual decline as seen in reality.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Epidemics can be modeled as diseases spreading over networks of contact between people.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Such a network can be represented mathematically with a graph and is called the contact network.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Every node in a contact network is a representation of an individual and each link (edge) between a pair of nodes represents the contact between them.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Links in the contact networks may be used to transmit the disease between the individuals and each disease has its own dynamics on top of its contact network.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The combination of disease dynamics under the influence of interventions, if any, on a contact network may be modeled with another network, known as a transmission network.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] In a transmission network, all the links are responsible for transmitting the disease.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] where ${\langle k\rangle }$ is the mean-degree (average degree) of the network and ${\langle k^{2}\rangle }$ is the second moment of the transmission network degree distribution.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] It is, however, not always straightforward to find the transmission network out of the contact network and the disease dynamics.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The *basic reproduction number* (denoted by *R*0) is a measure of how transferable a disease is.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] It is the average number of people that a single infectious person will infect over the course of their infection.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] An infectious disease is said to be endemic when it can be sustained in a population without the need for external inputs.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] This means that, on average, each infected person is infecting *exactly* one other person (any more and the number of people infected will grow sub-exponentially and there will be an epidemic, any less and the disease will die out).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The basic reproduction number (*R*0) of the disease, assuming everyone is susceptible, multiplied by the proportion of the population that is actually susceptible (*S*) must be one (since those who are not susceptible do not feature in our calculations as they cannot contract the disease).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Notice that this relation means that for a disease to be in the endemic steady state, the higher the basic reproduction number, the lower the proportion of the population susceptible must be, and vice versa.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] This expression has limitations concerning the susceptibility proportion, e.g. the *R*0 equals 0.5 implicates S has to be 2, however this proportion exceeds the population size.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Assume the rectangular stationary age distribution and let also the ages of infection have the same distribution for each birth year.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Let the average age of infection be *A*, for instance when individuals younger than *A* are susceptible and those older than *A* are immune (or infectious).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] We reiterate that *L* is the age at which in this model every individual is assumed to die.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] This provides a simple way to estimate the parameter *R*0 using easily available data.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] This allows for the basic reproduction number of a disease given *A* and *L* in either type of population distribution.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Compartmental models are formulated as Markov chains.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] A classic compartmental model in epidemiology is the SIR model, which may be used as a simple model for modelling epidemics.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Multiple other types of compartmental models are also employed.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Mathematical models need to integrate the increasing volume of data being generated on host-pathogen interactions.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Many theoretical studies of the population dynamics, structure and evolution of infectious diseases of plants and animals, including humans, are concerned with this problem.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] If the proportion of the population that is immune exceeds the herd immunity level for the disease, then the disease can no longer persist in the population and its transmission dies out.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Thus, a disease can be eliminated from a population if enough individuals are immune due to either vaccination or recovery from prior exposure to disease.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] For example, smallpox eradication, with the last wild case in 1977, and certification of the eradication of indigenous transmission of 2 of the 3 types of wild poliovirus (type 2 in 2015, after the last reported case in 1999, and type 3 in 2019, after the last reported case in 2012).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] The herd immunity level will be denoted *q*.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Remember that this is the threshold level.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Die out of transmission will only occur if the proportion of immune individuals *exceeds* this level due to a mass vaccination programme.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] We have just calculated the **critical immunization threshold** (denoted *qc*).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] It is the minimum proportion of the population that must be immunized at birth (or close to birth) in order for the infection to die out in the population.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] If the vaccine used is insufficiently effective or the required coverage cannot be reached, the program may fail to exceed *qc*.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Such a program will protect vaccinated individuals from disease, but may change the dynamics of transmission.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Suppose that a proportion of the population *q* (where *q* < *qc*) is immunised at birth against an infection with *R*0 > 1.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] This change occurs simply because there are now fewer susceptibles in the population who can be infected.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] *Rq* is simply *R*0 minus those that would normally be infected but that cannot be now since they are immune.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] As a consequence of this lower basic reproduction number, the average age of infection *A* will also change to some new value *Aq* in those who have been left unvaccinated.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Recall the relation that linked *R*0, *A* and *L*.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Thus, the vaccination program may raise the average age of infection, and unvaccinated individuals will experience a reduced force of infection due to the presence of the vaccinated group.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] For a disease that leads to greater clinical severity in older populations, the unvaccinated proportion of the population may experience the disease relatively later in life than would occur in the absence of vaccine.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] If a vaccination program causes the proportion of immune individuals in a population to exceed the critical threshold for a significant length of time, transmission of the infectious disease in that population will stop.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] If elimination occurs everywhere at the same time, then this can lead to eradication.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Interruption of endemic transmission of an infectious disease, which occurs if each infected individual infects less than one other, is achieved by maintaining vaccination coverage to keep the proportion of immune individuals above the critical immunization threshold.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Models have the advantage of examining multiple outcomes simultaneously, rather than making a single forecast.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/mathematical-modelling-of-infectious-diseases] Models have shown broad degrees of reliability in past pandemics, such as SARS, SARS-CoV-2, Swine flu, MERS and Ebola.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/next-generation-matrix] In epidemiology, the **next-generation matrix** is used to derive the basic reproduction number, for a compartmental model of the spread of infectious diseases.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/next-generation-matrix] In population dynamics it is used to compute the basic reproduction number for structured population models.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/next-generation-matrix] It is also used in multi-type branching models for analogous computations.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/next-generation-matrix] The method to compute the basic reproduction ratio using the next-generation matrix is given by Diekmann *et al.* (1990) and van den Driessche and Watmough (2002).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/next-generation-matrix] To calculate the basic reproduction number by using a next-generation matrix, the whole population is divided into n compartments in which there are $m<n$ infected compartments.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/next-generation-matrix] Let $x_{i},i=1,2,3,\ldots ,m$ be the numbers of infected individuals in the $i^{th}$ infected compartment at time *t*.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/next-generation-matrix] In the above equations, $F_{i}(x)$ represents the rate of appearance of new infections in compartment i . $V_{i}^{+}$ represents the rate of transfer of individuals into compartment i by all other means, and $V_{i}^{-}(x)$ represents the rate of transfer of individuals out of compartment i .
[src:epidemiological-modeling/next-generation-matrix] Let $x_{0}$ be the disease-free equilibrium.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/next-generation-matrix] Now, the matrix $FV^{-1}$ is known as the next-generation matrix.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/next-generation-matrix] The basic reproduction number of the model is then given by the eigenvalue of $FV^{-1}$ with the largest absolute value (the spectral radius of $FV^{-1}$ ).
[src:epidemiological-modeling/next-generation-matrix] Next generation matrices can be computationally evaluated from observational data, which is often the most productive approach where there are large numbers of compartments.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/serial-interval] The **serial interval** in the epidemiology of communicable (infectious) diseases is the time between successive cases in a chain of transmission.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/serial-interval] The serial interval is generally estimated from the interval between clinical onsets (if observable), in which case it is the 'clinical onset serial interval'.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/serial-interval] It could in principle be estimated by the time interval between infection and subsequent transmission.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/serial-interval] If the typical time from the first person's clinical onset to when they infect another is *TA*, and the incubation period of a subsequent case is *IB*, then the clinical onset serial interval is *TA + IB*.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/serial-interval] More realistically, the calculation would use the observed frequency distribution of times from onset of a single primary case to that of its associated secondary cases.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/serial-interval] If the distribution of timing of transmission events during the infectious period is not skewed around its mean, then the average serial interval is calculated as the sum of the average latent period (from infection to infectiousness) and half the average infectious period.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/serial-interval] Serial intervals can vary widely, especially for lifelong diseases such as HIV infection, chickenpox, and herpes.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/serial-interval] The serial interval for SARS was 7 days.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/serial-interval] For the original strain of COVID-19, a 2020 review of the published literature shows its serial interval to be 4-8 days.
[src:epidemiological-modeling/serial-interval] Related but distinct quantities include the 'average transmission interval' sum of average latent and infectious period, the 'incubation period' between infection and disease onset, and the 'latent period' between infection and infectiousness.
